'''Monica Avanesyan''' ({{lang-arm|<U+0544><U+0578><U+0576><U+056B><U+056F><U+0561> <U+0531><U+057E><U+0561><U+0576><U+0565><U+057D><U+0575><U+0561><U+0576>}}, born October 18, 1998) is an [[Armenia]]n teen singer who represented her country at the [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2013]] with her song "Choco Factory".

==Life and work==
Monica Avanesyan was born on October 18, 1998 is [[Yerevan]], the [[Armenia]]n capital city.  Avanesyan started becoming interested in music at the age of 3<U+00BD>, but began her singing career at the age of 5.  She started taking violin classes at age 7, then took dancing and singing lessons at age 10<U+00BD>.  In summer 2013, Avanesyan released her debut single, titled "Das Chem Anelu."

==Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2013==
On September 27, 2013, Monica Avanesyan competed in the Armenian national selection for the 11th [[JESC 2013|Junior Eurovision Song Contest]], with "Choco Factory," placing 1st in a field of 12 hopefuls, thus winning the right to represent the nation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Armenia: Monica Avanesyan Has Won|url=http://eurovoix.com/2013/09/27/armenia-monica-avanesyan-has-won/|last=Granger|first=Anthony|accessdate=27 September 2013|date=27 September 2013|publisher=Eurovoix}}</ref> In Kyiv, the song placed 6th with a score of 69 points, receiving 12 points from Georgia.

